## 6.3 Prediction Bias

### Purpose

Analyze bias caused by trades being triggered by, or conditioned on, an alpha signal.

### Setup / formulation

Prediction bias is defined as:

- Trades triggered by or considering an alpha signal exhibit bias when estimating their price impact.

Bouchaud et al. distinguish two forms:

- Larger order size $Q$ is more likely to come from stronger prediction signal.
- Faster execution may occur when short-term alpha is stronger.

The chapter introduces Simpson’s trading graph $S$ with variables:

- $\alpha$: alpha signal or alpha features.
- $Q$: trading process.
- $\Delta P$: contemporaneous return or slippage.

Causal links:

- $\alpha \to \Delta P$: alpha model.
- $\alpha \to Q$: control problem.
- $Q \to \Delta P$: price impact.

### Main result

Under Simpson’s trading graph,

$$
E[\Delta P \mid do(Q)] \neq E[\Delta P \mid Q].
$$

The impact counterfactual is biased if estimated naively from observational data.

### Interpretation

The naive conditional expectation $E[\Delta P \mid Q]$ mixes the effect of trading with the effect of the alpha that caused the trading. The do-expression $E[\Delta P \mid do(Q)]$ asks what would happen if the researcher externally set the trade, breaking the link from alpha to trade.

