## 6.3.1 Definitions

### Purpose

Define prediction bias and the causal structure used to study it.

### Setup / formulation

Simpson’s trading graph $S$ consists of:

$$
\alpha \to Q, \qquad \alpha \to \Delta P, \qquad Q \to \Delta P.
$$

Key assumption:

- The trading system allows no feedback loops.

In particular, the alpha signal should be exogenous to the trading process. Feedback between $Q$ and $\alpha$ creates difficult-to-identify causal biases and may introduce production instability.

### Main result

Prediction bias is formalized as:

$$
E[\Delta P \mid do(Q)] \neq E[\Delta P \mid Q].
$$

The failure occurs because $\alpha$ is a confounder for the relationship between $Q$ and $\Delta P$.

### Interpretation

A trader cannot estimate price impact simply by asking what happened historically after large trades. Large trades may have occurred precisely when the trader had strong predictive information.

