## 6.3.2.1 Why Is Impact Research Complex?

### Purpose

Explain why impact estimation is harder than alpha estimation.

### Setup / formulation

Let $\Delta I(\lambda,Q)$ be a return prediction from an impact model $I$ with parameter $\lambda$.

The following regressions are biased:

$$
\Delta P = \Delta I(\lambda,Q) + \epsilon,
$$

and

$$
\Delta P = \Delta I(\lambda,Q) + \beta \alpha_{\text{latest}} + \epsilon.
$$

The correct regression uses historical alpha:

$$
\Delta P = \Delta I(\lambda,Q) + \beta \alpha_{\text{historical}} + \epsilon.
$$

### Main result

The relevant control variable is not the researcher’s current alpha model. It is the point-in-time historical alpha signal that generated the historical trading process $Q$.

### Interpretation

If a trading team improves its alpha model over time, the latest version does not necessarily explain past trades. Impact researchers therefore need reproducible historical signals.

