## 6.3.3 Experiments and Regularization

### Purpose

Describe how interventional data can solve prediction bias when alpha is unavailable.

### Setup / formulation

Two experiments are considered:

- Submit random trades: $do(Q)$.
- Randomly do not submit trades: $do(Q=0)$.

Random trades identify impact:

$$
p(\Delta P \mid do(Q)).
$$

Randomly unsubmitted trades identify alpha:

$$
p(\Delta P \mid do(Q=0), \alpha).
$$

Interventional regressions include:

$$
\Delta P = \Delta I(\lambda,Q) + \epsilon \mid do(Q),
$$

and

$$
\Delta P = \beta \alpha + \epsilon \mid do(Q=0).
$$

### Main result

Randomized interventions break confounding paths and provide unbiased data. Causal regularization combines:

- Observational data: plentiful but biased.
- Interventional data: scarce but unbiased.

### Interpretation

A broker who does not observe client alpha cannot fix prediction bias by adding a better statistical model alone. The broker needs either alpha or randomized experiments. Causal regularization uses a small amount of randomized data to discipline a model trained on much larger historical data.

