## 6.3.4 Example: Impact-Adjusted Alpha Research

### Purpose

Show how prediction bias also affects alpha research when price impact is unknown.

### Setup / formulation

Suppose a trader has:

- $\alpha_{\text{historical}}$: historical alpha used to generate past trades.
- $\alpha_{\text{new}}$: a new alpha model.
- $I(\lambda,Q)$: an impact model.

Step 1: estimate impact using historical alpha:

$$
\Delta P = \Delta I(\lambda,Q) + \beta^h \alpha_{\text{historical}} + \epsilon.
$$

Step 2: compute unperturbed returns:

$$
\Delta S = \Delta P - \Delta I(\lambda,Q).
$$

Step 3: fit the new alpha:

$$
\Delta S = \beta^n \alpha_{\text{new}} + \epsilon'.
$$

### Main result

Impact-adjusted alpha research should first remove impact using a correctly estimated impact model, then fit the new alpha model on unperturbed returns.

### Interpretation

Without impact adjustment, alpha researchers can mistake their own market impact for predictive signal.

