## 6.4.1 Definitions

### Purpose

Define synchronization bias through the external trading graph.

### Setup / formulation

Synchronization bias is the possibility that the impact of a metaorder changes depending on whether other traders are executing similar metaorders at the same time.

The external trading graph contains two paths connecting $Q$ and $M$:

- Crowding path:

$$
Q \leftarrow \alpha \to M.
$$

- Leakage path:

$$
Q \to M.
$$

Two related counterfactuals are:

Crowding counterfactual:

$$
E[\Delta M \mid do(Q=0), \alpha].
$$

Leakage counterfactual:

$$
E[\Delta M \mid do(Q)].
$$

### Main result

Crowding is alpha-like: market trades happen because of common information. Leakage is impact-like: market trades occur because the trader’s own orders become visible or inferred.

### Interpretation

Crowding would have happened even if the trader did not trade. Leakage would not have happened without the trader’s order.

