## 6.4.2 Actions and Counterfactuals

### Purpose

State the main synchronization-bias counterfactuals and their identification formulas.

### Setup / formulation

The chapter considers four counterfactuals:

Impact with leakage:

$$
p(\Delta P \mid do(Q)).
$$

Impact without leakage:

$$
p(\Delta P \mid do(Q), do(M=0)).
$$

External impact:

$$
p(\Delta P \mid do(M)).
$$

Anonymity assumption counterfactual:

$$
\forall q \in \mathbb{R},
\quad
p(\Delta P \mid do(M=q), do(Q=0))
=
p(\Delta P \mid do(M=0), do(Q=q)).
$$

### Main result

Identifiability equations under the external trading graph include:

Impact with leakage:

$$
p(\Delta P \mid do(Q))
=
\int p(\Delta P \mid Q,\alpha)p(\alpha)d\alpha.
$$

Impact without leakage and anonymity-style interventions:

$$
p(\Delta P \mid do(Q), do(M))
=
\int p(\Delta P \mid Q,M,\alpha)p(\alpha)d\alpha.
$$

External impact:

$$
p(\Delta P \mid do(M))
=
\int p(\Delta P \mid M,Q,\alpha)p(Q,\alpha)dQd\alpha.
$$

Leakage:

$$
p(M \mid do(Q))
=
\int p(M \mid Q,\alpha)p(\alpha)d\alpha.
$$

Crowding:

$$
p(M \mid do(Q=0),\alpha)
=
p(M \mid Q=0,\alpha).
$$

### Interpretation

External impact is harder to estimate than internal impact because the trader does not control market flow $M$. The anonymity assumption is useful because it allows practitioners to treat the impact of market trades and trader trades as equivalent under some conditions.

