## 6.5.2 Actions and Counterfactuals

### Purpose

Distinguish impact with implicit microstructure from impact with explicit microstructure.

### Setup / formulation

Impact with implicit microstructure:

$$
p(\Delta P \mid do(Q)).
$$

Impact with explicit microstructure:

$$
p(\Delta P \mid do(Q^r)).
$$

Identification for implicit microstructure:

$$
p(\Delta P \mid do(Q))
=
\int p(\Delta P \mid Q,\alpha)p(\alpha)d\alpha.
$$

Identification for explicit microstructure:

$$
p(\Delta P \mid do(Q^r))
=
\int p(\Delta P \mid Q^r,\alpha,\alpha^{LL})p(\alpha,\alpha^{LL})d\alpha d\alpha^{LL}.
$$

Implementation bias is formalized as:

$$
p(\Delta P \mid do(Q^r))
\neq
\int p(\Delta P \mid Q^r,\alpha=x)p(\alpha=x)dx.
$$

The missing control is $\alpha^{LL}$.

### Main result

To estimate explicit microstructure impact, control for both $\alpha$ and $\alpha^{LL}$. To estimate strategic impact with implicit microstructure, controlling for $\alpha$ is sufficient under graph $L$.

### Interpretation

For most strategic execution applications, microstructure effects can be modeled implicitly. But if the researcher wants the impact of individual fills or tactical actions, the tactical signal must be part of the causal adjustment.

