## 6.5.3 Experiments and Regularization

### Purpose

Describe experiments and causal regularization for implementation bias.

### Setup / formulation

Three experiments are considered:

- Submit random trades: $do(Q)$.
- Randomly trade on tactics only: $do(Q=0)$.
- Randomly do not execute tactical deviations, producing a modified graph $L''$.

For tactics-only trading:

$$
p(\Delta P \mid do(Q^r), do(Q=0))
=
\int p(\Delta P \mid Q^r, do(Q=0), \alpha^{LL})p(\alpha^{LL})d\alpha^{LL}.
$$

For disabled tactical deviations on graph $L''$:

$$
p(\Delta P \mid do(Q^r), \alpha^{LL})
=
\int p(\Delta P \mid Q^r,\alpha^{LL},\alpha)p(\alpha)d\alpha.
$$

Causal regularization can transfer information from an implicit impact model to an explicit microstructure model. If $\lambda^i$ is the implicit-model parameter and $\lambda^e$ is the explicit-model parameter, the regularization penalty is:

$$
\theta \|\lambda^i - \lambda^e\|^2.
$$

### Main result

Explicit microstructure impact is difficult to estimate because it requires control over both strategic and tactical alpha. Causal regularization can use the better-understood implicit impact model as a prior for the more granular explicit model.

### Interpretation

If the explicit microstructure model is data-poor or hard to identify, it should not be estimated from scratch. It can be shrunk toward the standard strategic impact model.

