## 6.6.1 Definitions

### Purpose

Define issuer bias and the time-aware graph.

### Setup / formulation

Issuer bias depends on the word “dependent.” Successive orders may be dependent because:

- The first alpha affects the second alpha: $\alpha_1 \to \alpha_2$.
- The first order affects the second order: $Q_1 \to Q_2$.

Examples:

- Mean-reversion signals can generate alpha autocorrelation.
- End-of-day inventory constraints can create future-volume dependence.

### Main result

Successive metaorders require a time-aware causal graph. Treating them as independent observations biases follow-up impact estimates.

### Interpretation

Issuer bias is a causal version of order autocorrelation. The second trade is not just another sample; it may be causally linked to the first trade.

