## 6.6.3 Experiments and Regularization

### Purpose

Describe experiments and regularization for issuer bias.

### Setup / formulation

The chapter considers submitting order sequences with random signs.

This differs from randomizing each order independently:

- The causal link $Q_1 \to Q_2$ is preserved.
- The initial sign of the sequence is randomized.

Under the modified graph $T'$:

$$
p(Q_2 \mid do(Q_1)) = p(Q_2 \mid Q_1).
$$

For regularization, if $\lambda_t$ is the impact parameter at time $t$, then a smoothing penalty is:

$$
\theta \|\lambda_2 - \lambda_1\|^2.
$$

In a multi-period case:

$$
\theta \sum_t \|\lambda_{t+1} - \lambda_t\|^2.
$$

### Main result

Random-sign order sequences identify the future-volume counterfactual while preserving sequential dependence. Regularization can smooth impact parameters over time.

### Interpretation

Issuer bias is hard to isolate experimentally because the time-aware graph is heavily connected. Regularization helps by imposing smoothness or transfer learning from nearby periods.

