## Chapter-level summary

- The chapter applies causal inference to price impact estimation.
- The central problem is that observed trading data is usually endogenous.
- Causal graphs document assumptions about trading systems and markets.
- The key distinction is between passive conditioning $p(Y \mid X)$ and intervention $p(Y \mid do(X))$.
- Prediction bias occurs when alpha causes both trades and returns.
- Synchronization bias occurs when the trader’s flow and market flow interact through crowding or leakage.
- Implementation bias occurs when realized trades are selected by tactical low-latency signals.
- Issuer bias occurs when successive metaorders are causally dependent.
- Some biases can be removed by conditioning on the correct historical variables.
- Some biases require interventional data from randomized trading experiments.
- Causal regularization combines large biased observational datasets with small unbiased interventional datasets.
- The chapter’s results apply beyond linear regressions to any model consistent with the causal graph.
- Causal graphs also help with experiment design, simulation, infrastructure design, and stakeholder communication.

